          "Tokenization is the step that turns raw text into the integer ids the model consumes. Word-level vocabularies explode in size and choke on rare or unseen words; character-level keeps the vocabulary tiny but makes sequences very long and forces the model to relearn spelling from scratch. Subword tokenization is the middle ground, and byte-pair encoding (BPE) is the dominant algorithm. BPE starts from a base vocabulary and greedily merges the most frequent adjacent pair into a new token, repeating until it reaches a target vocabulary size; common words end up as single tokens while rare words split into reusable subword pieces.",
          "Modern GPT-style models use byte-level BPE, which starts from the 256 possible bytes rather than Unicode characters. This guarantees there are no out-of-vocabulary tokens at all: any string, including emoji, code, and unseen scripts, is representable as a sequence of byte tokens. Concrete vocabulary sizes are worth knowing: GPT-2 used 50,257 tokens, GPT-4 uses cl100k_base at roughly 100k tokens, and GPT-4o uses o200k_base at roughly 200k tokens. A larger vocabulary fits more text per token (fewer tokens for the same text, so cheaper calls and longer effective context) at the cost of a bigger embedding and output table.",
