          "After retrieval and reranking you must assemble the context window, and this stage has its own failure mode. The lost-in-the-middle effect, documented by Liu et al. (2023), is that LLMs attend most reliably to information at the beginning and end of a long context and can effectively ignore highly relevant text buried in the middle, producing a U-shaped accuracy curve that mirrors the primacy and recency effects in human memory. The practical consequences: do not dump 50 chunks just because the window is large, order matters, and more context is not strictly better. Place the strongest reranked chunks at the head and tail, and keep the number of chunks small, which is exactly why reranking down to a handful pays off.",
          "Build the assembled context deliberately rather than concatenating blindly. Deduplicate near-identical chunks (overlapping windows produce redundant hits), include the source and section as an inline citation handle so the model can attribute and you can verify, and respect the token budget by reserving room for the system prompt, the question, and the answer. Long-context models do not eliminate retrieval. Stuffing the whole corpus is slower, more expensive per token, and still degrades via lost-in-the-middle, whereas tight RAG sends only what is needed. A good line: the context window is a scarce, position-sensitive resource, and assembly is ranking plus packing, not just paste.",
