          "Generation failures mean the context was correct but the answer is wrong or unsupported. The headline is hallucination, where the model asserts facts not in the context; combat it by instructing answer-from-context-only, lowering temperature, adding citation requirements, and measuring faithfulness or groundedness. A subtler failure is the model ignoring provided context in favor of its priors, which lost-in-the-middle ordering and tighter context sets reduce. Outdated or conflicting sources cause confidently wrong answers; fix with freshness metadata, recency-aware ranking, and de-duplication so two contradictory versions do not both make the cut.",
          "Operational failures round out the list. No-context queries (nothing relevant exists) should trigger an explicit abstention or a fallback, not a fabricated answer, so add a relevance threshold on retrieval scores. Multi-hop questions that require combining several documents defeat single-shot retrieval; address with query decomposition or iterative or agentic retrieval. Access-control leakage, where retrieval returns a chunk the user is not allowed to see, is a security bug, not a quality bug, so enforce tenant and ACL filters in the vector query itself rather than filtering after the fact. The meta-point that lands well: RAG is a pipeline, and you debug it by attributing each bad answer to retrieval, ranking, or generation, then fixing that stage."
