          "Name the non-obvious operational concerns that separate staff from senior. For generative apps: hallucination control via contextual grounding in Guardrails plus citation from Knowledge Bases; evaluation via Bedrock model evaluation and an LLM-as-judge or human review loop; cost control via batch, prompt caching, and distillation; latency via cross-Region inference profiles and streaming responses. For custom models: training/serving skew solved by Feature Store, drift caught by Model Monitor, and reproducibility enforced by Pipelines and the Model Registry. Mentioning data residency (cross-Region inference may move data between Regions, so check compliance) and that Bedrock does not use your prompts to train base models are the kind of details that build trust.",
          "On the behavioral side, these companies run structured loops and Amazon-style bar-raiser interviews are common across the industry, so prepare crisp STAR (Situation, Task, Action, Result) stories. Amazon currently has 16 Leadership Principles, unchanged since the 2021 addition of 'Strive to be Earth's Best Employer' and 'Success and Scale Bring Broad Responsibility'. If a Leadership-Principles-style interview comes up, map each story to a principle, lead with the metric, and use 'I' not 'we' to claim your specific actions. Do not assert an interview format you have not confirmed; verify each company's process from their careers page or recruiter rather than guessing. For the technical AI rounds, the winning pattern is the same every time: restate the requirement, name the tier and why, sketch the data flow, then close with cost, safety, and observability trade-offs."
